== Controversy == The Akademi is an autonomous body empowered by its constitution to elect its chairman through a [[Electoral system|voting process]] by the 41 members of the general body.<ref name="The Indian Express 2015">{{cite web | title=Bharat Mehta returns state Akademi award | website=The Indian Express | date=2015-11-04 | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/bharat-mehta-returns-state-akademi-award/ | access-date=2017-10-25}}</ref>
The Akademi did not have a chairman from 2003 to 2015 as the government did not held an election.<ref name=AGSI/> It was run by the registrar in-charge and the secretary of the sports, youth and cultural activities department; ex-offcio. In April 2015, the state government appointed Bhagyesh Jha, a Gujarati writer and retired [[Indian Administrative Services|IAS]] officer, as the new chairman of the Akademi without any election.<ref name="IndiaTimes2017"/> This resulted in the Autonomous Academy Agitation (''Swayatta Akademi Andolan'') led by [[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]], the oldest literary institute in Gujarat and several Gujarati writers including Manishi Jani, [[Shirish Panchal]], [[Dhiru Parikh]], [[Chandrakant Topiwala]], Bharat Mehta, Paresh Naik and Raju Solanki.<ref name="The Indian Express 2011">{{cite web | title=Writers demand autonomy for Sahitya Academy | website=The Indian Express | date=2011-06-06 | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/writers-demand-autonomy-for-sahitya-academy/ | access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> Parishad boycotted the activities of the Akademi in protest. In March 2016, the Gujarati poet [[Harsh Brahmbhatt]] declined the award which had been conferred to him by the Akademi for his book.<ref name="The Indian Express 2016">{{cite web | title=Writer declines award from ‘non-autonomous’ Academy | website=The Indian Express | date=2016-03-29 | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/writer-declines-award-from-non-autonomous-academy/ | access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> In November 2015, Bhagyesh Jha and two other writers [[Chinu Modi]] and [[Vinod Bhatt]], said to be the supporter of Jha, used the word ''[[Taliban]]'' for the writers like [[Dhiru Parikh]] and [[Niranjan Bhagat]], who had supported the agitation. [[Pravin Pandya]] returned the award he had received in 2004 in protest.<ref name="The Times of India 2016">{{cite web | title=Writer returns award to Gujarat Sahitya Parishad | website=The Times of India | date=2016-01-15 | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Writer-returns-award-to-Gujarat-Sahitya-Parishad/articleshow/49613917.cms | access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> Another Gujarati writer and literary critic, Bharat Mehta, returned the award which he had received in 2008.<ref name="The Indian Express 2015"/> Dhiru Parikh, along with other writers, submitted a [[public interest litigation]] to the [[Gujarat High Court]].<ref name="The Indian Express 2015"/><ref name="The Times of India 2016"/><ref name="IndiaTimes2017"/>
